Anonymous Fri 06 Dec 2019 03:13:45 No.26953709 Report
Quoted By: >>26954094 >>26954209
>>26953479

Plenty of elements.
Is there a conflict? I'll use a couple examples from recent stories. In The Heartless Ranger, the MC takes a posting his friend just abandoned, and finds himself under the command of said Ranger. How is he going to integrate into the team and deal with her?
Or in Proper Care of Construction Equipment , the MC is hurt in an accident while on the job. The female lead is said construction equipment, significantly larger & taller. What happens after the accident, and how do they overcome their differences during casual interaction as demonstrated by the last scene?
Having good internal and external conflicts keep the characters moving.
But...what if there is no conflict?
Showing two (or more) people interacting can be fun to write and read, but the interaction should feel well rounded. This can be nice for short, single scene stories, or character sketches.

Anonymous Fri 06 Dec 2019 03:17:53 No.26953760 Report
Quoted By: >>26953888
>>26953479
Here's my advise. Take a premise, from a prompt bucket or one you come up with. Like when I started writing HSR I knew I wanted to write a romance between a mentally scarred veteran and a reporter. I had already made the Sci-Fi universe from my DnD campaigns with the lads. I don't do plotting in the conventional sense, I write out key events after an initially planned beginning, I make a series of events that are going to happen in the story. After planning the events I put them on notecards and arrange them until I like the order, I call it dynamic plot. Like I knew I wanted Julia and Anon to have a nice dinner and go see a play preformed by moth and butterfly anthros from the start. So added it as a plot point and I finally filled it in a place where it fitted nicely, though I added Anon's first bout with PTSD before it to keep it as a potential event.
As for A New King, I took an idea from the thread and wrote out a scenario in a pre-built fantasy universe.
Always worldbuild fully before you write as it helps prevent Tolkienitis (over explaining everything.).
Though that's just my advise. If you need a prompt take one from one of the several buckets or expand upon one in the greentext bucket.

Anonymous Fri 06 Dec 2019 03:38:41 No.26954094 Report
Quoted By: >>26954209
>>26953709

Next, motivation.
This isn't the conflict. The longer the piece, the more you need to know the characters.
In one of mine, I knew from the beginning roughly what the characters were doing. As things happened their backstory emerged, and that's what ended up telling me how they approached these one or two sentence cues I had as an outline. Don't worry, I didn't know until the end of the first draft who my narrator was and what drove him.
I'm working on a re-write where I'm switching the POV character. Old one, motivations too clear. New one, conflicted to hell and back, needs and wants a change, and is doing something about it.
And a note on worldbuilding. A_Smiling_Face is right, but leave room. Only you will know the scope and detail you need.
For me, I started with two caveats on my world. It would be an alternate earth with one tiny change, and that historical events came to the same resolution but perhaps by different means. So I didn't need to explain my world in many ways; the characters feel perfectly normal seeing a non-human. OTOH, because I finished it first I had the opportunity to re-think infodumps on the background of the world. Show your world as much as possible, reveal it through dialogue, make the reader earn it. It should never feel like a wikipedia article

Quoted By:
>>26953479
I'm not qualified to give writing advice, but as someone who only really got into it recently, I find a vague outline to be the best motivator. It gives you a clear goal, but allows you to adjust things as you need and can even give you problems to solve.
Did I plan on writing about a group of mutual rape victims getting on a boat to Canada? Well partially, but the rest came to me as I wrote it and needed to find a semi-believable way for them to make some real progress on the map.
Don't be afraid to write some weird shit or even stuff you aren't totally confident in. You have to at least get a rough idea out there before you can really make it something you're happy with.

TLDR: Write for fun and worry about polishing it later. If you aren't having fun coming up with potential ideas, don't write it.

Add the two: 97 + 46 = 143
If >=100 ignore 1xx: 100 = 00
143 = 43

[She is...]
Use 2nd to Last: >>--------4-

[You are...]
Use Last Digit: >>---------6

Digits: 43 , 4 , 6

1 just visiting, or passing through

There are dozens (or hundreds or thousands) of "methods." If it was a simple formula, then everyone could write and just keep pumping out formulaic sewage like endless police & crime "dramas" or "funny" sitcoms. Without knowing more about you, your personality, how you go about imagineering, it's almost impossible to help here in this thread.

But, there are several writefag generals that pop up on various 4chan boards. You'll have to explore around and find a board & community that seems active in ways that you feel you can participate and get value back out. Of course, start with the /trash/ writefag general. It's almost always active and filled with denizens that might be closer to what you're looking for. Y'know. Given /trash/ taste in subject matter.

There are many styles of writing. Identify several and practice them. Pretend to be a news reporter, write a scientific paper, compose a short story in verse. Think of creative ways to fully convey a concept or scene. Do it in 250 words. Study what needs expansion, redo it in 500 or 1000 words.

Like drawing, the advice is draw draw draw all day long. Same with writing. Write write write. Write a half page piece of a conversation. Write six pages to describe a piece of history for a world. Write two pages to describe a characters favorite food. On a planet in the Andromeda galaxy.

Envision the last half page of a story, the scene, the dialog. How it reveals the last moments the characters will ever see in writing. Write that page.

Then write the story that came before that moment.

I'll give you more detail. I wrote a rather long piece that I felt good about. A former (female) co-worker and I talked a good bit about amateur writing. After I finished the first draft, we mutually challenged each other to do first reader duties.
While hers is still in the first draft phase, she helped to massively highlight issues that I couldn't see. As a writer the scene/world/universe is in your head. The reader only has what you put in words.
Her input help make the female characters more vivid, and the male lead more consistent. She saw his character growth in a way I didn't and couldn't.
The hard part is that for a you have to trust that person with a creation you've nurtured for months. On the other hand, watching someone else build a story (or world) and asking questions was one of the best learning experiences across any field I've attempted
